":"1230–1280","1230–1267":"1230–1267","1236":"1236","1267":"1267","1300":"1300","1230":"1230","about 1300":"circa 1300","1270":"1270","c. 1270":"circa 1270","1280":"1280","Pulford, Cheshire, England":"Pulford, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"c. 1270–":"about 1270–Deceased","1236–Male":"1236–Deceased","1270–Female":"1270–Deceased","1270–Male":"1270–Deceased","1300–1300":"1300–1300","1230–1280":"1230–1280","1230–1267":"1230–1267","1236":"1236","1267":"1267","1300":"1300","1230":"1230","about 1300":"about 1300","1270":"1270","c. 1270":"about 1270","1280":"1280","Pulford, Cheshire, England":"Pulford, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","of, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hammond","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Ha(i)mon</i>, the oblique case form of the ancient Germanic <i>Ha(i)mo</i>, a short form of various compound names beginning with <i>haim</i> ‘home’. It frequently developed excrescent <i>-d</i>, giving <i>Hamond</i>, <i>Haimund</i>, and <i>Hawmond</i>. Alternatively, the name could derive from the Middle English personal name <i>Hamund</i> (Old Norse <i>Hámundr</i>, composed of the elements <i>hár</i> ‘high’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protection’), which may have been used in Normandy and in 12th-century eastern England, but the former explanation is more likely. The surname was sometimes confused with   Almond   and   Ammon  .","English: in the Bradford area of Yorkshire, the name is a shortened form of <b>Ormondroyd</b>, formerly <i>Hamondesrode</i>, from a lost place in Birstall (Yorkshire), named with the Middle English (Old French) personal name <i>Hamon</i> (1 above) + Middle English <i>roid</i>, a southern Yorkshire pronunciation of Old English <i>rod</i> ‘clearing’.","Irish: generally an importation from England, but occasionally an adopted name for <b>Mac Ámoinn</b>, see   McCammon  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hammonds","meanings":["English (Shropshire and Staffordshire): variant of   Hammond  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Almond","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Almund</i>, in which Old English <i>Æthelmund</i> ‘noble protector’ and <i>Ealhmund</i> ‘temple protector’ have coalesced.","variant of   Allman   and   Allmand   both meaning ‘German’, assimilated by folk etymology to the vocabulary word denoting the tree."]},{"name":"Hammett","meanings":["English (southwestern England, especialy Devon): from the Middle English personal name <i>Hamet</i>, a pet form of ancient Germanic <i>Hamo</i> (see   Hammond   1)."]},{"name":"Hamon","meanings":["Breton, French, and English (Channel Islands): from the Breton, Old French, Middle English personal name <i>Hamon</i>, the oblique case form of the ancient Germanic <i>Ha(i)mo</i>, a short form of various compound names beginning with <i>haim</i> ‘home’. See also   Hammond  ."]},{"name":"Hamlin","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, from the Norman French and Middle English personal name <i>Hamelin</i>, a double diminutive of <i>Hamo</i> (see   Hammond  ).","French: variant of   Hamelin   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this.","Americanized form of Finnish <b>Hämäläinen</b> (see   Hamalainen  )."]},{"name":"Hampson","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): patronymic from the Norman personal name <i>Hamo</i>, <i>Hamon</i> (see   Hammond  ).","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hAmhsaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Amhsach</i>’ a byname meaning ‘mercenary soldier’ or ‘messenger’, from the adjective <i>amhasach</i> ‘aggressive’."]},{"name":"Haimes","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Yacov, Yosef.","English: variant, with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, of <b>Haime</b>, of Norman origin, from the Old French personal name <i>Haim</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Haimo</i>, from <i>haim-</i> ‘home’), often Latinized as <i>Hamo</i>. Compare   Hammond  .","Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) Jewish surname."]},{"name":"Hammon","meanings":["English (Middlesex and Ken): variant of   Hammond  ."]}]},{"name":"Jonet","type":"FIRST","meanings":["A Scottish form of Janet."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Jonet Hammond was born about 1270, in Pulford, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Robert Hammond, Knight de Pulford, was 41 and her mother, Elizabeth Oddyle, was 41. She had at least 1 daughter with Sir. Hugh Brickill."},"et":{"c. 1270–":"umbes 1270–Surnud","1236–Male":"1236–Surnud","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1300–1300":"1300–1300","1230–1280":"1230–1280","1230–1267":"1230–1267","1236":"1236","1267":"1267","1300":"1300","1230":"1230","about 1300":"umbes 1300","1270":"1270","c. 1270":"umbes 1270","1280":"1280","Pulford, Cheshire, England":"Pulford, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"c. 1270–":"noin 1270–Kuollut","1236–Male":"1236–Kuollut","1270–Female":"1270–Kuollut","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1300–1300":"1300–1300","1230–1280":"1230–1280","1230–1267":"1230–1267","1236":"1236","1267":"1267","1300":"1300","1230":"1230","about 1300":"noin 1300","1270":"1270","c. 1270":"noin 1270","1280":"1280","Pulford, Cheshire, England":"Pulford, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","of, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"c. 1270–":"environ 1270–Décédée","1236–Male":"1236–Décédé","1270–Female":"1270–Décédée","1270–Male":"1270–Décédé","1300–1300":"1300–1300","1230–1280":"1230–1280","1230–1267":"1230–1267","1236":"1236","1267":"1267","1300":"1300","1230":"1230","about 1300":"environ 1300","1270":"1270","c. 1270":"environ 1270","1280":"1280","Pulford, Cheshire, England":"Pulford, Cheshire, Angleterre, Roya